Thanks for reporting this. The behavior is intentional on Apple and Android: you need to set `e.Handled = true` in your `Touch` event handler (at minimum on the `Pressed` action) to tell the platform that you are consuming the touch — otherwise the underlying platform drops subsequent move/release events.

For example:
```csharp
void OnTouch(object sender, SKTouchEventArgs e)
{
    if (e.ActionType == SKTouchAction.Pressed)
        e.Handled = true;

    // process e.Location etc.
}
```

This is modeled after [HandledMouseEventArgs](https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/api/system.windows.forms.handledmouseeventargs.handled): if you choose not to handle a touch you won't receive further events for that touch sequence, allowing parent views to receive them instead.

That said, the cross-platform inconsistency raised in the comments is valid — WinUI fires all pointer events regardless of `Handled`, while Apple and Android require it. This behavioral gap is worth addressing to make the cross-platform contract consistent.
